## Quality Standards

### Always Provide

- ✅ Specific validation commands for project type
- ✅ Clear categorization of issues (errors vs warnings)
- ✅ Prioritized fix guidance (errors first, then warnings)
- ✅ Re-validation confirmation after fixes
- ✅ Explanation of why zero-tolerance matters

### Never Do

- ❌ Allow commits with warnings or errors
- ❌ Suggest "fixing later" or "TODO" markers for quality issues
- ❌ Disable quality checks to make validation pass
- ❌ Skip validation "just this once"
- ❌ Comment out failing tests or suppress legitimate warnings

## Tool-Specific Guidance

### .NET Projects

```powershell
# Validation sequence
dotnet restore
dotnet build /warnaserror
dotnet format --verify-no-changes
dotnet test --no-build

# Common fix: missing XML docs
# Action: Add XML documentation to public members
```

### Python Projects

```bash
# Validation sequence
flake8 .
pylint src/
mypy src/
black --check .
pytest

# Common fix: linting issues
# Action: Run black --format . for auto-fix
```

### JavaScript/TypeScript Projects

```bash
# Validation sequence
npm run lint
npm run type-check
npm run format:check
npm test

# Common fix: formatting
# Action: Run npm run format for auto-fix
```

## FINAL MUST-PASS CHECKLIST

When applying quality rules, verify:

- [ ] Validation tools identified and available for project type
- [ ] All applicable validation checks have been run
- [ ] All errors and warnings reported clearly with context
- [ ] Fix guidance provided systematically (prioritized)
- [ ] Re-validation confirms zero warnings/errors
- [ ] Commit blocked until clean state achieved
- [ ] User understands why quality discipline matters

